WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.640
Thank you all for being here, my name is Kelly, I teach statistics and data science, and on

00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:15.840
this first slide you are seeing the beautiful city of Barcelona, Spain, and I put that up

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:21.240
there because a week from today I will hopefully be there to meet my boyfriend's parents for

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:22.240
the first time.

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:31.400
He is fully Spanish, I very wisely took 10 years of French, so I don't really speak Spanish,

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:37.279
and I have been practicing a bit, and so that has gotten me thinking a little about translating

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:42.639
between ordinary languages and translating between programming languages.

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:46.520
And so this whole hook was of course just an excuse for me to be like, hey everyone,

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:50.560
I have a boyfriend, that's him.

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:55.680
And so I have been listening to this podcast that teaches Spanish, and there was this phrase

00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:00.040
that they were teaching that kind of struck me, and it looked like this, me gusta ver

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:07.279
a mis amigos, sorry for the pronunciation, and that a, the ver a mis amigos was the point

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:13.120
of the episode, it's kind of a weird construction for what they are trying to say is, I like

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:14.739
to see my friends.

00:01:14.739 --> 00:01:19.239
But of course if you were to translate word for word or literally to English, we would

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:24.440
be saying, it is pleasing to me to see to my friends, which of course is not a thing

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:29.959
that we say in English, and so this got me thinking about that idea of a one-to-one direct

00:01:29.959 --> 00:01:35.099
translation and how that's not really how languages actually work.

00:01:35.099 --> 00:01:42.800
So can we apply this sort of theory of language learning to programming languages instead?

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:46.599
So I'd like to start off with a pop quiz, it's the first talk of this year's conf besides

00:01:46.599 --> 00:01:51.360
the keynote, and I'm hitting you with a quiz, sorry not sorry, here's your pop quiz.

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:56.879
Oops, I don't know why that's not showing, okay, you get my pop quiz in words.

00:01:56.879 --> 00:02:02.720
This code right here, is the object returned by that code going to be two-dimensional,

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:06.879
like a matrix or a data frame or something with rows and columns, or is it going to be

00:02:06.879 --> 00:02:09.160
one-dimensional, like a vector or an array?

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:11.160
Who's going to say one-dimensional?

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:14.160
Who's going to say two-dimensional?

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:20.199
Kudos to you people who raised your hands for two-dimensional after seeing the one-dimensional.

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:24.800
The answer, as you might expect, is it's a trick question, as we know, Posit is no longer

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:26.919
an R-only company.

00:02:26.919 --> 00:02:32.240
In R, this exact code right here, taking a column of a penguin's data set, is going to

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:34.199
be one-dimensional, right?

00:02:34.199 --> 00:02:36.039
That's yanking out a column.

00:02:36.039 --> 00:02:41.559
In Python, that thing's two-dimensional, that is a data frame with one column.

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:46.399
This is an example of, there is not a direct translation between these two rather similar,

00:02:46.399 --> 00:02:49.039
rather close languages.

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:52.720
That exact code will run in both languages, and it will produce a different structure

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:56.039
of results.

00:02:56.039 --> 00:02:57.679
So what motivated this?

00:02:57.679 --> 00:03:02.119
There's a class that I teach every year at Cal Poly, it's called Statistical Learning,

00:03:02.119 --> 00:03:07.960
and we're upgrading it to Statistical Learning with R, but then I've added in the Python.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:11.919
This class is kind of an upper-level class, it's mostly, but not entirely, stat majors

00:03:11.919 --> 00:03:15.800
in their final years of their undergrad degree.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:21.720
There's no computing prerequisite, I think we're going to change that.

00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:25.600
There's no computing prerequisite, so any R or Python that I use, I have to kind of

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:28.720
spoon-feed a little bit.

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:33.240
Back when this class was first offered, 2020, I didn't teach it, it used kind of a hodgepodge,

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:38.479
as many of us have done with modeling, it was using caret, and base R, and tidyverse

00:03:38.479 --> 00:03:42.279
for the data wrangling, and just kind of all over the place.

00:03:42.279 --> 00:03:47.479
So when I took it over, I changed it to tidymodels, and that was really fun, tidymodels was kind

00:03:47.479 --> 00:03:50.800
of new, and it made it so much easier to teach it, I could go on, but that's not the point

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:53.199
of this talk.

00:03:53.199 --> 00:03:56.479
And then this year, for some reason, instead of doing the smart thing and just reusing

00:03:56.479 --> 00:04:00.960
my materials with little tweaks that had gone very well, I decided to translate everything

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:05.240
also into scikit-learn in Python.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:07.479
So I want to tell you what this talk isn't.

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:09.279
I am not encouraging you to do this.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:14.080
This is extra work for me, without a huge amount of benefit in the class.

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:17.359
I am not trying to encourage you to teach a bilingual class, although if you're interested,

00:04:17.359 --> 00:04:19.440
I would love to talk to you about it.

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.640
I did it kind of because there's sort of these two funnels into this course, and one side

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:29.119
of that funnel is the computer science data science minors, I wanted it to be accessible.

00:04:29.119 --> 00:04:34.480
I wanted it to fit in our eventual data science bachelor's program, and I really wanted to

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:37.959
practice, and it's one of those things where you commit when you're feeling enthusiastic

00:04:37.959 --> 00:04:39.959
and then you're forced into it.

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:44.160
So I wanted to practice Python, I wanted to pick up Quarto, which is nice for using both.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:45.160
So that's why I did it.

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:46.160
So I'm not telling you to do it.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:47.160
I did it for fun.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:54.000
So that's not the point of this talk.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.519
So what is the point of this talk?

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:00.480
What I want to talk to you about is what I learned from watching the students learn

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:06.119
differently from these two languages, like the two cohorts who chose R versus Python.

00:05:06.119 --> 00:05:09.559
And specifically thinking about how these different implementations, not just across

00:05:09.559 --> 00:05:13.640
languages, but maybe even across packages, is going to impact understanding for these

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:14.640
users.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:19.799
And specifically, I know most people in this room maybe because of the track might be educators,

00:05:19.799 --> 00:05:24.920
but I kind of have split this out into advice for developers or creators, for users of the

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:32.760
tools, and then, of course, most importantly, for educators.

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:34.440
So let's just dive in.

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:38.519
So thinking about how you learn a new language or how you translate between languages.

00:05:38.519 --> 00:05:42.279
And now I'm thinking back to Spanish and French.

00:05:42.279 --> 00:05:45.679
Probably the first thing that comes to mind that's hard that was in my first example is

00:05:45.679 --> 00:05:46.679
grammar.

00:05:46.679 --> 00:05:48.279
And specifically sentence structure.

00:05:48.279 --> 00:05:54.640
Why do these same words go in a totally different order in different languages?

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:59.399
And so how I might kind of parallel that in programming languages is this idea of what's

00:05:59.399 --> 00:06:01.000
the structure of your analysis.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.559
You have to do these multiple steps to do an analysis.

00:06:04.559 --> 00:06:09.200
But in different implementations, those steps might happen at different times.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:10.320
So here's what I mean.

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:11.480
Here's two code chunks.

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:13.880
The top one is scikit-learn, is Python.

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:18.880
The bottom one down there is tidy model, is R, of course.

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:25.160
And my question to you is when in these two chunks do we decide which predictors are going

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:26.160
to go into our model?

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:30.600
It's just a linear model with a couple of predictors.

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:31.839
And that's happening right here.

00:06:31.839 --> 00:06:34.720
So it feels kind of the same in both languages right now.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:38.959
At the moment where you're fitting the data after you've specified your model, that's

00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:43.399
when you're declaring which variables are part of this model.

00:06:43.399 --> 00:06:45.420
But then you start thinking about preprocessing.

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:50.619
So here's some Python code that includes a step where we are log transforming both

00:06:50.619 --> 00:06:53.299
of our quantitative predictors.

00:06:53.299 --> 00:06:57.619
And so we've added some stuff to the process that you can see in Python.

00:06:57.619 --> 00:07:00.660
The preprocessing decision happens early.

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:04.579
And then the decision about which predictors we're actually doing that to happens at the

00:07:04.579 --> 00:07:11.059
fifth step.

00:07:11.059 --> 00:07:18.299
But in tidy models here, we now have this idea of recipes.

00:07:18.299 --> 00:07:25.100
So the recipe then contains both the decision about your predictors and the decision about

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:26.980
how you're going to transform them.

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:29.299
And even though it's all together, it's actually in the opposite order.

00:07:29.299 --> 00:07:33.019
You choose your predictors and then your transformations.

00:07:33.019 --> 00:07:34.739
And so this is slightly different.

00:07:34.739 --> 00:07:35.940
And I'm not saying it's wrong.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.739
I don't think that either one is necessarily wrong.

00:07:38.739 --> 00:07:42.899
But having different approaches is going to have consequences.

00:07:42.899 --> 00:07:45.059
And so here's what happened with my students.

00:07:45.059 --> 00:07:49.660
The ones that were using tidy models kind of focused really on feature selection.

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:53.260
They really focused on which predictors are going to be in my model.

00:07:53.260 --> 00:07:57.660
And then once they decided that, they were like, eh, maybe we could log transform them.

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:01.540
And the ones who used scikit-learn really focused on how do we adjust the data.

00:08:01.540 --> 00:08:04.500
They kind of thought of this transformation as part of the data cleaning.

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:11.140
And they did that first and then allowed some predictors or others to be in their model.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:12.940
So what's the takeaway from that observation?

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:17.980
Well, developers, I just want you to be aware of how, like, your API design is going to

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:21.260
influence how people think about the actual concepts.

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:22.260
Right?

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:25.619
This is not, like, a separate thing.

00:08:25.619 --> 00:08:31.980
And then I want, when possible, if you can be kind of agnostic, if you can allow, like,

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:37.140
I'm thinking of how, you know, the recipes and the model specification and tidy models,

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:38.940
it doesn't really matter which order you declare them.

00:08:38.940 --> 00:08:43.299
They're sort of separate entities that you put together later.

00:08:43.299 --> 00:08:46.859
I think that's a really good design choice, personally.

00:08:46.859 --> 00:08:50.780
And then my last suggestion is just keeping kind of related decisions together.

00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:54.299
Like, I don't necessarily think scikit-learn is wrong, but I don't like this thing that

00:08:54.299 --> 00:08:58.780
you go through the whole setup and then you specify your predictors.

00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:03.419
And of course you can insert steps where you make another data frame to kind of solve

00:09:03.419 --> 00:09:04.419
for that.

00:09:04.419 --> 00:09:10.299
But the way that it's sort of naturally set up doesn't keep those decisions together.

00:09:10.299 --> 00:09:14.820
My advice for users here, try to match your code flow with your narrative, where you have

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:15.820
choices.

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:20.380
You know, if you are thinking through a problem in a certain way, try to match your code.

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:22.739
And then, of course, like, intersperse your code with text.

00:09:22.739 --> 00:09:26.940
This is why that discussion and documentation is so important.

00:09:26.940 --> 00:09:30.179
If you're doing two parallel analyses in different languages, but you have to kind

00:09:30.179 --> 00:09:35.059
of shuffle parts of it, then you are going to need that discussion text to help match

00:09:35.059 --> 00:09:39.219
those up.

00:09:39.219 --> 00:09:43.539
And then as much as you can kind of compartmentalize, make your steps modular, here's where we choose

00:09:43.539 --> 00:09:50.979
the model, here's where we choose the predictors, that also kind of lets you swap between languages.

00:09:50.979 --> 00:09:54.780
And then my advice for educators here, you know, enforce a workflow on your students

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:59.820
that matches the way that you teach it.

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:00.820
Break your analyses up.

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:02.380
Same idea as the practitioners.

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:05.820
If you are isolating these decisions, then when they see them in different orders, they

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:09.059
recognize that decision.

00:10:09.059 --> 00:10:12.859
And then, you know, really push students to document, to write what they're doing, to

00:10:12.859 --> 00:10:16.299
state their decisions outside the context of the code.

00:10:16.299 --> 00:10:18.780
All right.

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:23.020
Next thing that I find difficult in learning languages is false friends, or faux amis, when

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:24.340
I learned French.

00:10:24.340 --> 00:10:27.179
Words that sound really similar and have different meanings.

00:10:27.179 --> 00:10:32.059
So if I come up to you later in this conference, and I say this, you're probably going to make

00:10:32.059 --> 00:10:36.260
that face if you are not a Spanish speaker, but it turns out I have learned that this

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:38.900
just means I have a cold, I'm kind of congested.

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:41.659
It doesn't mean what you might think.

00:10:41.659 --> 00:10:44.979
Or another one, if you come up to me and you say your talk was quite good, I'm going to

00:10:44.979 --> 00:10:50.900
be really happy, unless I find out that you are from the UK, where quite means like meh.

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:56.380
So this word quite in English does not mean the same thing in every culture.

00:10:56.380 --> 00:10:58.400
And so what does this look like in code?

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:03.859
What it looks like to me, you know, is similar functions or arguments that behave differently.

00:11:03.859 --> 00:11:07.340
So by way of example, I want to talk a little about support vector machines.

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:10.580
Not going to teach you support vector machines, I'm going to do this really quick.

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:14.299
We are trying to find a line to separate these two classes.

00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:17.700
We want that line to sort of push the classes apart as much as possible.

00:11:17.700 --> 00:11:21.500
So we want those dotted lines to be as far from the solid line.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:25.380
But as we push the classes apart, we end up with, on the right-hand side, those points

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:29.820
that are misclassified or that kind of fall inside that margin.

00:11:29.820 --> 00:11:34.219
So when we fit a support vector machine, we're trying to minimize that misclassification,

00:11:34.219 --> 00:11:35.219
maximize that margin.

00:11:35.219 --> 00:11:36.219
This is the push and pull.

00:11:36.219 --> 00:11:41.059
And so as you would hope, you know, in the implementation in tidy models, there is indeed

00:11:41.059 --> 00:11:46.020
a parameter that is the cost of having points fall inside of a margin.

00:11:46.020 --> 00:11:50.859
And in scikit-learn, as you would hope, there is a parameter C that has to do with the cost

00:11:50.859 --> 00:11:52.380
of points falling in the margin.

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:56.020
So let's look at those a little more closely.

00:11:56.020 --> 00:12:00.380
Tidy models version is the cost of predicting wrong.

00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:05.739
So the cost of a sample landing in the margin or like on the wrong side.

00:12:05.739 --> 00:12:09.539
In scikit-learn, notice that it says C. The strength of the regularization is inversely

00:12:09.539 --> 00:12:15.820
proportional to C. The regularization being that penalization for misclassification.

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:17.340
So these work opposite.

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:18.659
They're capturing the same thing.

00:12:18.659 --> 00:12:19.659
They're capturing the same idea.

00:12:19.659 --> 00:12:21.419
Again, neither is wrong.

00:12:21.419 --> 00:12:24.739
But when my students sitting next to each other using different languages tried the

00:12:24.739 --> 00:12:28.460
same values for cost and for C, because they were trying to tune their model, they got

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:29.460
different results.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:34.219
And that was very confusing to them and to me for quite some time.

00:12:34.219 --> 00:12:37.619
And so what happens here is that then those students, of course, like conceptualize that

00:12:37.619 --> 00:12:39.219
penalty differently.

00:12:39.219 --> 00:12:44.140
So the tidy model students are conceptualizing it as a penalty on misclassification, whereas

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:50.500
the scikit-learn students are conceptualizing it as like a balancing parameter, a regularization

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:51.500
parameter.

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:56.020
How much do we balance the margin, the desire for a wide margin with the desire for less

00:12:56.020 --> 00:12:58.580
points inside that margin?

00:12:58.580 --> 00:13:01.820
So it's, you know, again, not wrong, leads to different ideas.

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:06.859
And so what I would remind everyone to do is, you know, be explicit if you're designing

00:13:06.859 --> 00:13:07.859
tools.

00:13:07.859 --> 00:13:11.700
I think cost of misclassification helped me track down what was going on.

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:17.859
I think amount of regularization did not, because regularization is a little more general.

00:13:17.859 --> 00:13:22.539
And then, you know, I don't think I'm not asking for consistency in parameterization.

00:13:22.539 --> 00:13:24.940
I'm not asking that you make sure everything's the same.

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:28.380
I'm asking that you be up front, because it's not possible that everything's the same and

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:33.380
people like me need to be able to track down what the difference is.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:37.020
My advice for educators and practitioners, state everything in words.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:41.140
Say things like when the cost is higher, we expect less misclassification and the cost

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:42.940
of that is a smaller margin.

00:13:42.940 --> 00:13:48.179
If you say that out loud, then you are understanding that parameter.

00:13:48.179 --> 00:13:54.940
And then, as always, you know, translate these choices to non-code language.

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:56.299
Term three, moving swiftly along.

00:13:56.299 --> 00:13:59.619
I think that learning language's slang terms become hard.

00:13:59.619 --> 00:14:01.780
My favorite slang term in English is stand.

00:14:01.780 --> 00:14:04.619
You know, the phrase stand to stand something or to be a stand.

00:14:04.619 --> 00:14:07.700
It means you're like our big fan, basically.

00:14:07.700 --> 00:14:10.260
We're all stands of R in here.

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:13.500
How many of you know where it came from?

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:18.460
So this came from a music video and song by Eminem about a very obsessed fan whose name

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:20.580
was literally stand, like Stanley.

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:24.979
And somehow over the years, this word evolved to mean something much broader and something

00:14:24.979 --> 00:14:30.460
that is used, you know, and people don't even remember that it came from a person's name.

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:36.059
And so I think the equivalent of slang in code is maybe these helper wrapper functions

00:14:36.059 --> 00:14:40.859
that contain a whole lot of meaning, like way more than what that one word might suggest.

00:14:40.859 --> 00:14:46.460
And where I see this in my class is in tuning parameters.

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:50.820
So when you tune, and we're sticking here with those support vector machines.

00:14:50.820 --> 00:14:55.659
When you tune, you need to decide which values you're going to try, right?

00:14:55.659 --> 00:15:00.260
And in both Python on top and R on the bottom, you can just sort of manually create, you

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:05.419
know, kind of that list of different values that we're going to try for our model.

00:15:05.419 --> 00:15:12.979
The tidy models also comes with the shortcut where we can access built-in functions with

00:15:12.979 --> 00:15:18.419
the names of the parameters, and it will automatically choose values for you that it thinks are reasonable.

00:15:18.419 --> 00:15:19.419
I love this.

00:15:19.419 --> 00:15:20.419
I'm not saying this is bad.

00:15:20.419 --> 00:15:24.179
I would much rather have Max Kuhn decide which values I'm tuning than me decide.

00:15:24.179 --> 00:15:25.260
That's great, right?

00:15:25.260 --> 00:15:33.500
I don't know why .0009 and 32 are better choices than 10, 20, 30, but I assume Max does or

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:37.380
whoever wrote this part of tidy models, I'm fine with it.

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:40.820
But again, this was my biggest shock in the class.

00:15:40.820 --> 00:15:43.140
The Python students picked it up better.

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:46.859
Everyone understood tuning the first time that I taught it, and then nine weeks of hands-on

00:15:46.859 --> 00:15:50.900
activities later, if you asked the R students about tuning, they went into detail on the

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:51.900
functions.

00:15:51.900 --> 00:15:53.760
And if you asked the Python students, they got the concept.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:57.260
We just try a bunch of different values and see what sticks.

00:15:57.260 --> 00:15:58.859
So that was surprising to me.

00:15:58.859 --> 00:15:59.859
And so I don't really have advice.

00:15:59.859 --> 00:16:01.659
Like, these shortcut functions are great.

00:16:01.659 --> 00:16:02.659
I don't think they should change.

00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:05.099
I'm not saying that.

00:16:05.099 --> 00:16:11.539
I do think, like, again, that translating to English is a good thing, but most importantly

00:16:11.539 --> 00:16:14.979
for educators, like, not clicking for me.

00:16:14.979 --> 00:16:15.979
There we go.

00:16:15.979 --> 00:16:19.619
The educators, you know, think about if you're using a wrapper function, basically assume

00:16:19.619 --> 00:16:22.219
that what you're doing is glossing over that concept.

00:16:22.219 --> 00:16:23.219
So that's okay.

00:16:23.219 --> 00:16:24.340
Like, I do this with step PCA.

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:30.780
I don't teach all of PCA necessarily when I'm preprocessing, but avoid shortcut functions

00:16:30.780 --> 00:16:33.700
on things that are actually, like, learning goals in your class.

00:16:33.700 --> 00:16:34.700
Okay.

00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:41.020
