And I've learned that this is, like, a super cool cultural thing in Columbia that we don't

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:59.900
do in the U.S., is pointing with your lips.

00:16:59.900 --> 00:17:01.940
So here's your pop quiz in the code context.

00:17:01.940 --> 00:17:04.739
And I won't make you vote, because I'm low on time.

00:17:04.739 --> 00:17:09.739
How does the k-means function choose initial clusters?

00:17:09.739 --> 00:17:12.020
If you don't know k-means, ignore it.

00:17:12.020 --> 00:17:14.300
I asked this on Twitter.

00:17:14.300 --> 00:17:15.459
This is what people said.

00:17:15.459 --> 00:17:19.300
This is what I would have said before I dug into this.

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:20.459
And it is not correct.

00:17:20.459 --> 00:17:24.219
So here's how I used to teach k-means.

00:17:24.219 --> 00:17:28.060
Choose your initial centroids by choosing three random observations.

00:17:28.060 --> 00:17:30.300
Assign all the points to the nearest centroid.

00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:32.699
Recompute the centroids of each cluster.

00:17:32.699 --> 00:17:34.140
Keep going until you have clusters.

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:36.140
I've taught it that way for years.

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:40.619
It turns out that nothing about that is correct about how k-means actually works.

00:17:40.619 --> 00:17:41.619
I mean, it can be.

00:17:41.619 --> 00:17:42.619
You can set it to be.

00:17:42.619 --> 00:17:44.739
But that is not the default in this function.

00:17:44.739 --> 00:17:51.579
The default in this function, although it says that it will choose three initial observations,

00:17:51.579 --> 00:17:56.219
down there, that method, Hartigan-Wong default method, Hartigan-Wong neither initializes

00:17:56.380 --> 00:18:00.020
that way, nor does it even update in the same way as the other methods.

00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:04.099
So everything I've just told you is not the default.

00:18:04.099 --> 00:18:11.579
In scikit-learn, they're a little more upfront, but now this initialization, k++, that's different.

00:18:11.579 --> 00:18:15.380
At least they kind of explain it, but they just say it's smart.

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:20.380
And then you can think about using different functions in R. That one contains k++.

00:18:20.380 --> 00:18:25.459
k++ is not an option to the base k-means function.

00:18:25.459 --> 00:18:29.859
But now we don't have an option to choose your iteration process.

00:18:29.859 --> 00:18:34.140
So there is literally no way to guarantee, at least with these two implementations, that

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:37.859
the R and the Python output matches.

00:18:37.859 --> 00:18:39.579
And so what was the results?

00:18:39.579 --> 00:18:40.579
Just frustration.

00:18:40.579 --> 00:18:45.500
Just you cannot make that output be the same with the implementations people use.

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:46.500
And so I think these get repeated.

00:18:46.500 --> 00:18:50.939
I'm going to skip to kind of my final takeaways, because they contain those ones.

00:18:50.939 --> 00:18:52.619
So recap.

00:18:52.619 --> 00:18:57.859
We have these challenges, and these challenges that you see in language also appear in coding.

00:18:57.859 --> 00:19:00.739
So the developers in the room, what I want you to do.

00:19:00.739 --> 00:19:05.699
Don't assume that the choice of the parameter name tells people what that parameter does.

00:19:05.699 --> 00:19:08.420
Don't assume that these default choices are the obvious choices.

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:09.420
They're not universal.

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:11.800
You have to document them.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:16.180
And the order that we code is the order that we think.

00:19:16.180 --> 00:19:20.540
For practitioners, again, translation is not going to be a direct word for word.

00:19:20.540 --> 00:19:22.140
Please discuss what you're deciding.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:23.339
Please document.

00:19:23.339 --> 00:19:25.540
Please use text.

00:19:25.540 --> 00:19:30.260
And for educators, really what you want to do is force your students to be explicit about

00:19:30.260 --> 00:19:32.939
every decision.

